## Ignoring specific headings

[Decorative headings](Numbering.qd#decorative-headings) are not numbered and do not appear in the table of contents. A heading is marked as decorative if a `!` is appended to the last `#` sign. For example: `#!`, `##!`, `###!`, etc.

```markdown
##! A decorative heading
```

Decorative headings can appear in the table of contents if the optional `includeunnumbered` parameter is enabled:

```markdown
.tableofcontents includeunnumbered:{yes}
```

## Custom numbering

You can set a custom numbering format via `.numbering`. See [Numbering](Numbering.qd) for more information.

## Focusing and markers

If `focus:{A.B}` is added to the previous example:

!(550)[Table of contents with focus](Table-of-contents/focused.png)

Focusing can be particularly useful in slides with mini tables of contents at the beginning of each new chapter. In that case, consider defining a function like this:

```markdown
.function {chapter}
    name:
    .tableofcontents maxdepth:{0} focus:{.name}
    .marker {.name}
```

You can invoke it by `.chapter {My chapter}`.

The `.marker` function creates an invisible level-0 heading (which is not normally possible with the standard `#`-based heading syntax). Setting `maxdepth:{0}` displays only markers in the table of contents, ignoring other headings.
